Skellig Micheal is rocky crag off the cost of Kerry. It's a UNESCO World Heritage Site with a large (and fairly tame) puffin population. I personally think it's the most beautiful place in Ireland.
These photos are from a trip though Connemara to Roundstone. I was using a bridge camera, so the image quality (and corrective editing) is questionable
Lough Atalia was the first place I noticed the resurgence of egrets in Ireland. They started nesting in Ireland in 1997, and have become increasingly common since then.

The Saltee islands are a pair of privately-owned islands south of County Wexford. It has recently been granted the Special Protection Area to protect the bird habitat, which from my photos includes puffins, gulls, gormorants, gannets, and razorbills.

One of the stranger residents of london are the pelicans of St. James Park. They were introduced in 1664 by the Russian Ambassador, and since then have surprised tourists by occasionally eating Pigeons
There is one photo I unfortunately missed; Hundreds of swifts flew along the streets of La Palma, it was really beautiful but sadly too difficult for me to photograph.

Midwinter wildlife photography is challenging in Ireland; there just isn't enough light for much of the day. Lighting aside, I got extremely lucky and managed to get a picture of our elusive (but recovering) pine-marten

Killarney is home to the last native red deer in Ireland. In "rutting season", the stags bellow and battle each other for mates. I risked getting close (at some personal risk) to get better photos, until an extremely irritated park ranger caught up to me. But at that point, I had the photos!
I was lucky enough to see the small-clawed otters at feeding time. They were extremely noisy and pleased by their meals, and I got a few cute videos and pictures
I got a free ticket to this airshow; the formations flew by my apartment and I noticed after a few helicopters flew by

One of the locals along the Grand Canal feeds herons fish every day, so the buildings are sentied by herons waiting for dinner. I doubt she's popular with her neighbours; herons are colloquially known as 'shitepokes' due to their habit of ... when taking off. The paint-jobs of the expensive cars here are a bit tarnished

I saw a large number of wasps in the bushes in Lincoln Park Zoo. I wanted a photo, but as a rule of thumb, large nest-building wasps are fairly aggressive. I quickly searched Wikipedia, and made a plausible guess at the species (Sphex pensylvanicus, the great black wasp). It appeared to be a digger wasp, and by my theory should be fairly friendly. Thankfully, they didn't prove me wrong.
After visiting the International Crane Foundation, I have the rare accolade of having seen every extant crane species on the planet
I visited Dublin Zoo to get a picture of the recently arrived Dhole - a red-brown asian canine. It politely posed for me.

Killarney National Park is one of the easier places to spot Red Deer in Ireland. I'd visited the year before, and taken many more photos, but it was nice to get a lucky (if distant) photo of a Kestrel on the trip down

Lapwings are Ireland's national bird. Their population has declined due to habitat loss and changes in farming practice (they are ground-nesting like curlews). I was lucky enough to see a few lapwings in a ploughed field near Emo, Co. Laois. They are graceful fliers and have an especially beautiful song

During this visit to Ballyfin Nature Hide I managed to get some nice photos of our native red squirrel. The invasive grey squirrel population is more common in the east, but fortunately it seems that the slower grey squirrels cannot coexist with pine-martens while our red squirrels can

The biodiversity and presence of nature in Wisconsin was surprising. Practically every lamp-post had a percehd red-tailed hawk, vultures were circling over the fields, and there were several osprey over the lakes. The abundance of nature was enviable from an Irish perspective
Burr Point is the easternmost point of mainland Ireland.

I was lucky enough to visit while Berlin snowed & was fairly quiet. The architecture was beautiful, and I enjoyed walking through Tiergarten. I briefly, nominally, visited Museum Island, but got distracted and decided to walk around in the snow instead.

It is impressive how a stunt pilot can deliberately stall, flat spin, and generally abuse their plane while staying in the air. For a few moments I was genuinely worried they would drop into the Irish Sea.

One of our prettier villages. There was a nice poem enscribed by the gigantic wicker curlew:
"Hearing his voice, a god who had made the curlew would almost instantly want to remake himself as the thing he had made"

I visited to see the Giant Pandas Yang Guang and Tian Tian before they were recalled to China. Sadly, I was only succesful in seeing them turnt away in a corner sleeping. The red panda was thankfully more photogenic
The London Wetland Centre was suitable named; it was pouring when I visited. I managed to see the large lapwing population that visits during winter, and some unexpected eurasian cranes

Last year, three notoriously unreliable US V-22 Osprey's flew across central Dublin for an American College Football game in the Aviva stadium. This year, presumably for reasons of safety or Irish neutrality, we instead diverted a US-Boston flight which flew about 200m above the stadium. Less dramatic, but it's stil uncanny seeing a place fly so low across the city
I briefly visited Cherbourg for about three hours after a very long ferry from Rosslare.

Córdoba is obscenely pretty. The Mosque-Cathedral has striking rows of Moorish Ablaq arches and a beautiful orange grove courtyard. The 331 metre Roman bridge across the Guadalquivir river gave me a great view of the city, and I saw to animals I've been trying to photograph for years; a kingfisher and an eurasian otter. I only successfully photographed the latter

I only briefly visited Cádiz (an coastal Phoenecian-founded city in Andalusia) so took less photos than I ought to have. I was amazed my how many birds of prey I saw on the trip there from Seville, it would have been an amazing place to take wildlife photos. Next time...
Dalkey Island is home to the red-listed roseate tern, and a herd of feral goats that I was informed have become more friendly since people started feeding them regularly
Photos from the Chester Beatty Library, our National Archeology Museum, and Collin's Barracks museums.

I visited Granada at the end of a long trip through Spain. The Nasrid palaces are the most beautiful buildings I've ever seen or am likely to see. I really like Islamic tilework (which is obvious from how prevelant pictures of tilework are in this album) and the Alhambra has many beautiful variations (at least twelve of seventeen possible wallpaper symmetry groups)

Ireland's Eye is a small island off the coast of Howth, underneath the flight path into Dublin. It's the first part of Ireland I'd fly over returning to Ireland, but it took me a long time to actually visit it. Like our other island's (Saltees, Skellig Micheal, etc) it is home to puffins, gannets, and other photogenic sea-birds

On this trip I visited the V&A Museum and the Science musesum. I stayed in the Vanterbilt-mansion-turnt-middling-hotel (I couldn't pass up that opportunity). I hadn't looked up what was on display in the V&A (I was going because it was recommended to me), but I was surprised to see a (casting, presumable) of Michelangelo's David.

We visited Mount Teide at night with a tour group, and took photos at 2,500m altitude (well above the lights and clouds). The milky way was clearly visible, and it was possible to distinguish the colour of stars. My 84mm equivalent Voigtländer lens was surprisingly adept at astrophotography, though my gerry-rigged tripod (a folded-up coat) was not ideal.

Two beautiful countries. I probably didnt' see the best of Norway staying in Oslo (it's nice, but I really should have went hiking and exploring the countryside). The train-trip from Oslo to Stockholm was nice; the landscape was pretty different between the two countries. Norway seemed more densely forested, Sweden had endless lakes.

I was pleasantly surprised to see Fieldfares in summer; they migrate to Ireland in winter but I had no idea where they migrated back to.

I was lucky enough to photograph hundreds of migratory storks circling on the thermals above the city. I've often spotted them before nested from trains while travelling through the continent, but have never got a decent photo of even one.
I spotted these birds getting a taxi from South Dublin to the centre. The next day, I spent the afternoon squinting at the sun and spinning in circles trying to get the birds in focus.

I didn't see the rainforests near Anaga this trip, but the wildlife and flora were still amazing. There's swifts and parrots everywhere, and the forests along Mount Teide are really beautiful (though sadly unphotograpphed this time)

The highlight of my trip to York was renting an extremely slow-moving boat, sailing it with a mild sense of panic, and carefully navigating around the occasional geese that were floating down the river Ouse.

Anaga Rural Park is located in Macizo de Anaga, a cool, damp, cloudy mountain range. It's a laurel rainforest (which bears an odd resemblence to the remnants of Killarney's temperate rainforest) with many endemic species.
I briefly visited Cologne for a work conference. I didn't get much time for sightseeing, but I did at least see the enormous cathedral
Conwy is a compact town with an enormous castle. It's visitable from Dublin with an overnight stay, but barely (ferry's are slow!)
I was lucky enough to spot and (badly) photograph a raven for the first time while hiking up the cliffs overlooking Howth.
San Cristóbal de La Laguna is a UNESCO world-heritage site due to its early grid-pattern non-fortified colonial town layout
The weather was variable when I visited, and apocalyptic one memorable night.

Most of these photos are from the Madrid Zoo. The giant panda (Jin Xi I think) posed nicely, unlike the other pandas I've encountered (which mostly hid or turnt their backs to me). I took a lot of photos of the wildlife that lived in the zoo; there were dozens of white stork nests, and I was lucky enough to get a distant photo of a hoopoe.
I normally travel to rush around and see the sights. I did this less than normal when visiting Tenerife; so, lots of pictures of me meandering around Puerto de la Cruz.

I finally took some pictures of the birds of prey I'd see as while travelling between cities in Spain; red kites and eurasian griffon vultures were circling the fields around the train-station outside Segovia. The city itself, as expected, was beautiful.

Sintra was more verdant than I expected; it reminded me a little of Anaga's rainforest. I visited the Castle of the Moors and took a (bad) photo of Pena Palace from a castle turret. I'd checked beforehand that I could take a photo of that palace from the castle, but didn't account for lighting.

Slovenia is a wonderful, forested country with enormous mountain ranges and beautiful architecture from various eras (a lot of Yugoslav buildings & monuments are still standing in the capital Ljublana). It's also home to the olm, a blind cave-dwelling neotenous salamander (that was surprisingly difficult to photograph).

Toledo is a beautiful hilltop city not far from Madrid. It has a history of religious diversity, with synagogues, mosques, and churches built in the same city (and with architectural styles overlapping in interesting ways in Sinagoga del Tránsito). My picture of the city and the Alcázar was taken by frantically running off the tourist bus, grabbing a few hasty photos from a nearby wall, and running back to the bus before I was stranded.
Zaragoza has some of the northmost examples of Islamic architecture in Spain. Several buildings in the city are included in the UNESCO heritage site "Mujédar Architecture of Aragon"

I saw a sign in Bath saying "meet the Gorgon", and I did not turn down the chance.
I was listening to the Tannhauser Overture while walking through Tiergarten, so it was fitting to run into a Wagner statue.
A statue of Isambard Kingdom Brunel at Temple-Meads train station.

I was pleasantly surprised to see an isotype book in the Science Museum. I first came across the technique in the Handbook of Tyranny, it's an underused way of sharing data in an accesible way.
